<Layout title="Frailty & Geriatric Assessment Tools" description="Frailty and geriatric assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Frailty &amp; Geriatric</div>
  <h1>Frailty &amp; Geriatric Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Comprehensive tools for identifying frailty, assessing geriatric syndromes, and supporting caregiver assessment.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>CGA (Comprehensive Geriatric Assessment)</strong> — Multidimensional evaluation of older adults addressing medical conditions, function, cognition, mood, social circumstances, and environment; informs individualized care planning.</li>
      <li><strong>FRAIL Scale</strong> — Five-item frailty screening: Fatigue, Resistance (stair climbing), Ambulation, Illnesses ≥5, Loss of weight &gt;5%. Score ≥3 = frail; 1–2 = pre-frail.</li>
      <li><strong>Clinical Frailty Scale (CFS)</strong> — Nine-level pictorial frailty scale from Very Fit (1) to Terminally Ill (9); used in acute care, ICU, and primary care for rapid frailty classification.</li>
      <li><strong>Edmonton Frail Scale (EFS)</strong> — 11-item frailty screen assessing cognition (clock drawing), general health, functional independence, social support, medication use, nutrition, mood, and continence.</li>
      <li><strong>Fried Frailty Phenotype</strong> — Five-criterion frailty definition: unintentional weight loss, exhaustion, low physical activity, slow gait speed, weak grip strength. 3+ criteria = frail; 1–2 = pre-frail.</li>
      <li><strong>GFI (Groningen Frailty Indicator)</strong> — 15-item self-report frailty measure covering mobility, fitness, vision, hearing, nutrition, cognition, depression, loneliness, and social functioning. Score ≥4 indicates frailty.</li>
      <li><strong>Zarit Burden Interview (Caregiver Burden Scale)</strong> — 22-item scale measuring subjective caregiver burden from dementia caregiving. Score 0–20 little/no burden; 21–40 mild-moderate; 41–60 moderate-severe; 61–88 severe burden.</li>
      <li><strong>Social Isolation Assessment</strong> — Structured screening for social isolation risk factors including living alone, limited social contacts, transportation barriers, and community disconnection.</li>
      <li><strong>Elder Abuse Screening (EAS / EASI)</strong> — Elder Abuse Suspicion Index: 6-question clinician tool for detecting elder abuse, neglect, and exploitation in community-dwelling older adults.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
